diagnoses.name: Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.description: A type of kidney disease that involves glomeruli. Due to inflammation, the kidney's ability to filter waste and fluids from the blood is impaired. Symptoms may include foot edema and hematuria, which could lead to anemia.

diagnoses.name: Pyelonephritis
diagnoses.description: A type of urinary tract infection that ascends to the kidney, leading to inflammation. Symptoms often include flank pain, fever, and pyuria. It can also cause leukocytosis as a response to infection.

diagnoses.name: Sickle Cell Disease
diagnoses.description: A genetic blood disorder that leads to chronic anemia, among other complications. It can cause leukocytosis as part of the inflammatory response and may manifest with swelling in the hands and feet, though foot edema is not exclusively described.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction
diagnoses.description: Certain medications can induce reactions leading to various symptoms, including skin erythema, edema, and systemic reactions such as leukocytosis and anemia due to the body's response to the drug.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: A disease that can develop after an infection with group A Streptococcus bacteria. It can cause erythema marginatum (a specific type of skin rash), polyarthritis (including foot edema), and leukocytosis due to the inflammatory response.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: A disease caused by infection with group A streptococcus bacteria, leading to a characteristic rash, tongue erythema (strawberry tongue), and sometimes complications including pyuria. Anemia and leukocytosis can occur due to bacterial toxin effects and the body's response.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: The most common type of anemia, which may be secondary to chronic kidney disease (manifesting with symptoms like foot edema) or chronic infections leading to pyuria. It doesn't directly cause leukocytosis but can appear in conjunction with conditions that do.

diagnoses.name: Heart Failure
diagnoses.description: Chronic condition where the heart's ability to pump efficiently is compromised. It can cause systemic symptoms including foot edema due to fluid buildup. Anemia and leukocytosis can occur in chronic disease states.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schonlein Purpura (HSP)
diagnoses.description: A form of vasculitis affecting the small blood vessels that can lead to a rash, abdominal pain, kidney involvement (potentially leading to hematuria and pyuria), and joint swelling (like foot edema). Anemia and leukocytosis can occur due to the inflammatory process.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A severe reaction to medication or infection that causes the skin to blister and peel, leading to widespread erythema, including the tongue. It can cause systemic symptoms like fever, and possibly leukocytosis, but typically not foot edema or reported anemia as primary symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Measles
diagnoses.description: A viral infection that affects the respiratory system. The disease presents with a characteristic rash, fever, conjunctivitis, and Koplik's spots.

diagnoses.name: Ehrlichiosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial illness transmitted by ticks that causes flu-like symptoms, which may include a rash and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's characterized by fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, irritation and redness of the white part of the eyes (conjunctivitis), swollen lymph nodes, and mucous membrane changes.

diagnoses.name: Toxic shock syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain types of bacterial infections. Often associated with tampon use, this condition can lead to symptoms such as rash, fever, and low blood pressure.

diagnoses.name: Rocky Mountain spotted fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection transmitted by a tick. Early signs and symptoms often involve a severe headache and a rash that usually appears a few days after fever starts.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet fever
diagnoses.description: An infection that can develop in people who have strep throat. It's marked by a bright red rash that covers most of the body, fever, and sore throat.

diagnoses.name: Rubella (German Measles)
diagnoses.description: A contagious viral infection best known by its distinctive red rash. It is usually a mild illness, but its significance increases during pregnancy due to the potential to cause congenital rubella syndrome in the fetus.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein purpura
diagnoses.description: A disease that causes the small blood vessels in your body to become inflamed and leak. It results in skin rash, joint pain, gastrointestinal problems, and in some cases complications with the kidneys (pyuria).

diagnoses.name: Drug reactions
diagnoses.description: Adverse reactions to medications can cause a variety of symptoms including rash, fever, and in severe cases, leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and damage to various body parts including joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs. Symptoms include fatigue, joint pain, rash, and fever.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.reason: Symptoms including hypermobility and fatigue are common in Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes.

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.reason: May present with fatigue, attention deficit, and is commonly associated with conditions like Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS/ME)
diagnoses.reason: Presents with significant fatigue and can also involve immune system issues leading to increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.reason: Symptoms include fatigue and attention deficits. While not directly causing pseudoseizures, the stress from constant pain might contribute.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.reason: Could explain fatigue, attention deficit, and might have episodes that mimic seizures (pseudoseizures). Also associated with higher rates of infection due to immune system involvement.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reason: Presents a wide range of symptoms including increased susceptibility to infections, fatigue, and neuropsychiatric symptoms that could resemble pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency Disorders
diagnoses.reason: Directly responsible for increased susceptibility to infection. Accompanying fatigue is also common.

diagnoses.name: Psychogenic Non-Epileptic Seizures (PNES)
diagnoses.reason: Directly corresponds to pseudoseizures. Attention deficit and fatigue could be related symptoms or contributing factors.

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.reason: Primary symptoms include attention deficit. ADHD can co-occur with conditions like fibromyalgia which might explain the fatigue.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reason: Can present with a broad range of symptoms including increased susceptibility to infection, fatigue, and neurological manifestations that could mimic pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A type of blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells. These excess cells thicken the blood, slowing its flow, and can cause complications such as decreased appetite and episodic weakness.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic disorder characterized by high blood sugar levels over a prolonged period. Glycemic lability and polycythemia can be complications of poorly managed diabetes.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: Chronic kidney disease can lead to a decrease in kidney function over time. Impaired function can result in polycythemia and episodic weakness due to the accumulation of waste products in the blood.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones. Symptoms can include decreased appetite and hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that affects hearing and balance, potentially causing hearing loss. Its influence on nearby structures can sometimes manifest in varied systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It can cause symptoms like episodic weakness and, in rare cases, hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Mitochondrial Myopathies
diagnoses.description: A group of neuromuscular diseases caused by damage to the mitochondria, the energy-producing structures in cells. Symptoms can include episodic weakness and hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs from exposure to high cortisol levels for a long time. It can cause glucose intolerance (glycemic lability) and decrease in appetite as symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Autonomic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A group of symptoms that occur when there is damage to nerves that regulate blood pressure, heart rate, bowel or bladder control, and digestion. It can cause episodic weakness and glycemic lability.

diagnoses.name: Meniere’s Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In its broad symptomatology, it might indirectly contribute to or exacerbate other symptoms like episodic weakness.

diagnoses.name: Joint Hypermobility Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition that features joints that easily move beyond the normal range expected for a particular joint, possibly associated with pain, attention deficit, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)
diagnoses.description: A condition where a change from lying to standing causes an abnormally large increase in heart rate, which can cause presyncope or lightheadedness, along with other symptoms like fatigue, attention issues, and sometimes pain.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. Often seen with symptoms such as presyncope, attention deficits, and generalized pain.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. Can be associated with symptoms such as vulvodynia and joint hypermobility.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. Features often include hypermobility, skin elasticity, and fragile tissues.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder characterized by feelings of worry, anxiety, or fear that are strong enough to interfere with one's daily activities. Symptoms may sometimes mimic or worsen physical symptoms like presyncope.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Can cause a wide range of symptoms, including joint pain (potentially leading to hypermobility issues), neurological problems (such as attention deficits), and more.

diagnoses.name: Vulvar Vestibulitis Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A subtype of vulvodynia that is characterized by pain concentrated at the vestibule, the area surrounding the opening of the vagina. It can be associated with chronic pain conditions.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by excessive anxiety and worry about various topics, events, or activities. Symptoms might include physical manifestations such as fatigue or even presyncope under high stress.

diagnoses.name: Psychogenic Non-epileptic Seizures (PNES)
diagnoses.description: A type of disorder in which psychological stress causes physical symptoms that resemble seizures, including episodes of presyncope or

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones. Hypothyroidism may not cause noticeable symptoms in the early stages, but over time, untreated hypothyroidism can cause a number of health problems, such as obesity, joint pain, infertility, and heart disease.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by two most common symptoms - dry eyes and a dry mouth. The condition often accompanies other immune system disorders, such as rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complicated disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. The fatigue may worsen with physical or mental activity but doesn't improve with rest.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. Researchers believe that fibromyalgia amplifies painful sensations by affecting the way your brain processes pain signals.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age. Women with PCOS may have infrequent or prolonged menstrual periods or excess male hormone (androgen) levels. The ovaries may develop numerous small collections of fluid (follicles) and fail to regularly release eggs.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: A mood disorder that causes a persistent feeling of sadness and loss of interest. Also called major depressive disorder or clinical depression, it affects how you feel, think, and behave and can lead to a variety of emotional and physical problems.

diagnoses.name: Menopause
diagnoses.description: The time that marks the end of your menstrual cycles. It's diagnosed after you've gone 12 months without a menstrual period. Menopause can happen in your 40s or 50s, but the average age is 51 in the United States.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: A group of mental illnesses that cause constant and overwhelming anxiety and fear. Excessive anxiety can make you avoid work, school, family get-togethers, and other social situations that might trigger or worsen your symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. In rheumatoid arthritis, the body's immune system attacks its own tissue, including joints. In severe cases, it attacks internal organs.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that result in too much sugar in the blood (high blood glucose). There are several types of diabetes, including Type 1, Type 2, and gestational diabetes. They have different causes but share the symptom of having too much glucose in your blood.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones, potentially causing decreased libido and can sometimes lead to changes in behavior.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory lung disease that causes obstructed airflow from the lungs, which can lead to wheezing. It is unrelated to basophilia but could coexist in a patient with another underlying condition causing basophilia.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder characterized by feelings of worry, anxiety, or fear that are strong enough to interfere with one's daily activities. Often includes symptoms like obsessive-compulsive behaviors. Though not directly causing the other listed symptoms, anxiety can exacerbate or contribute to health issues in a multifactorial manner.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)
diagnoses.description: A disorder in which people have recurring, unwanted thoughts, ideas or sensations (obsessions) that make them feel driven to do something repetitively (compulsions). While not directly linked to the other symptoms, it is crucial to address in the presence of reported obsessive-compulsive behavior.

diagnoses.name: Cardiac Failure
diagnoses.description: A chronic progressive condition that affects the pumping power of your heart muscles. While not directly causing basophilia, it can lead to migratory edema as a symptom of the body's inability to manage fluid properly.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myeloid Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that begins in the blood-forming cells of the bone marrow and leads to an increase in the number of white cells in the blood, including basophils. This can cause various systemic symptoms including fatigue which might indirectly affect libido.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Reactions
diagnoses.description: An immune system response to a foreign substance that's not typically harmful to your body. These foreign substances are called allergens. They can include certain foods, pollen, or pet dander and can cause symptoms like wheezing and basophilia in severe reactions.

diagnoses.name: Asthma
diagnoses.description: A condition in which a person's airways become inflamed, narrow and swell, and produce extra mucus, which makes it difficult to breathe. Asthma can cause wheezing and is often associated with other allergic conditions that could indirectly relate to basophilia.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: A common and serious medical illness that negatively affects how you feel, the way you think, and how you act. It can lead to a variety of emotional and physical problems, including a decrease in libido.

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition in which high numbers of eosinophils (a type of white blood cell) are found in the blood over a long time, but other symptoms might mimic those associated with basophilia, and is often associated with allergic reactions and less commonly with edema.

diagnoses.comments: Leukoplakia can sometimes be confused with or related to oral lichen planus, especially when accompanied by irritability and depressive symptoms due to discomfort and chronic nature.
Leukoplakia is a potential precancerous condition. Patients exhibiting this symptom should be evaluated for oral cancer, especially if symptomatic for an extended period.
Symptoms such as presyncope and depression can be related to anemia. Endometriosis can contribute to iron deficiency anemia due to menstrual blood loss.
Can cause depression, irritability, and menstrual irregularities, which might be linked with endometriosis symptoms.
Though not directly associated with leukoplakia or presyncope, PCOS can manifest with endometriosis, irritability, and depressive episodes due to hormonal fluctuations.

Chronic pain condition that might be considered given the irritability and depressiveness, alongside other systemic symptoms. However, direct correlation with leukoplakia or endometriosis is not established.
Can cause depression and irritability due to malabsorption and its psychological impact. Indirectly related to other symptoms through systemic inflammation.
Could explain depression, irritability, and presyncope due to anemia. Some links to oral health issues provide a tenuous connection to leukoplakia.
While primarily related to endometriosis, this diagnosis should be considered in the differential due to shared risk factors and symptomatology overlap including severe menstrual irregularities.
Irritability and depression are key symptoms of chronic anxiety. Presyncope could also relate to panic attacks or acute stress responses.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur rapidly. Symptoms can include angioedema, rashes, and physical sensitivities.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and tissue damage throughout the body. Symptoms can include chest pain, rashes, and photosensitivity.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that affect how your body uses blood sugar (glucose). Glycemic lability is a hallmark of poorly controlled diabetes.

diagnoses.name: Myocardial Infarction
diagnoses.description: Commonly known as a heart attack, it occurs when blood flow decreases or stops to a part of the heart, causing damage to the heart muscle. Chest pain is a common symptom.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition that causes severe swelling in various parts of the body, including the limbs, face, intestinal tract, and airways.

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A severe drug reaction affecting the skin and other organs. Symptoms can include rashes, fever, lymphadenopathy, and in severe cases, angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Panic Disorder
diagnoses.description: A psychiatric disorder characterized by sudden episodes of intense fear that trigger severe physical reactions when there is no real danger or apparent cause. Can include chest pain and physical sensitivities.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of your skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. Symptoms can include rashes and angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Hypersensitivity Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that causes changes in the skin, such as rashes and angioedema. It can be a reaction to an infection or a foreign substance, such as a drug.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An uncommon inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash. Symptoms can include chest pain, rashes, and physical sensitivities.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraines that involve visual disturbances, including symptoms like scintillation and scotoma, and can also involve sensory disturbances like parasthesia.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it can lead to temporary neurological disruptions such as dysarthria and vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease affecting the central nervous system, causing symptoms like parasthesia, dysarthria, and sometimes visual disruptions.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke can affect various parts of the brain, potentially causing vertigo, dysarthria, and visual impairments.

diagnoses.name: Basilar Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that can involve aura, vertigo, dysarthria, and visual disturbances such as scintillation and scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy (Partial Seizures)
diagnoses.description: Particular types of epilepsy can manifest with sensory disturbances (e.g., scintillation, parasthesia) and sometimes with speech disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Depending on its location, a brain tumor can lead to a variety of neurological symptoms, including those listed.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition where blood flow to the back of the brain is compromised, leading to symptoms like dizziness (vertigo), visual disturbances, and speech difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing vertigo, hearing loss, and tinnitus, but can sometimes overlap with neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that primarily affects the vestibular system, leading to severe vertigo alongside migraine symptoms, which could include visual and sensory disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord, causing a range of neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by a blockage or hemorrhage in the brain's blood vessels, leading to neurological deficits.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that involves visual disturbances such as scotomas and scintillations, along with other sensory disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Basilar-type Migraine
diagnoses.description: A rare form of migraine that can cause vertigo, ataxia, and other brainstem-related symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain, which can cause a variety of neurological symptoms depending on its location.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a 'mini-stroke,' this is a temporary blockage of blood flow to the brain, leading to reversible neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from reduced blood flow in the posterior circulation of the brain, leading to symptoms like vertigo and ataxia.

diagnoses.name: Arnold-Chiari Malformation
diagnoses.description: A condition where brain tissue extends into the spinal canal, causing a variety of neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that weakens skeletal muscles, which can impact swallowing (dysphagia) and other muscular functions.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the nerve that connects the ear to the brain, leading to hearing loss, vertigo, and other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms may include sudden weakness, confusion, difficulty speaking, and vision problems.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraine with aura is a type of migraine that involves neurological phenomena (aura) before the actual migraine headache begins. The aura can include visual disturbances like scintillation, as well as sensory, speech, or motor disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Symptoms can include headaches, changes in speech or vision, and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: A transient ischemic attack (TIA), often called a mini-stroke, is a temporary period of symptoms similar to those of a stroke. A TIA usually lasts only a few minutes and doesn't cause permanent damage. Symptoms can include weakness, trouble speaking, and loss of balance or coordination.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms include fatigue, weakness, and vision problems.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: Epilepsy is a central nervous system (neurological) disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness. Certain types of epilepsy present with visual disturbances as part of the aura preceding a seizure.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: Meningitis is an inflammation of the fluid and membranes (meninges) surrounding your brain and spinal cord. The swelling from meningitis typically triggers symptoms such as headache, fever, and a stiff neck. In severe cases, neurological symptoms such as confusion and seizures can occur.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Encephalitis is inflammation of the brain caused by an infection or an autoimmune response. The condition causes flu-like symptoms, such as a fever or severe headache, as well as confusion, seizures, and problems with senses or movement, including vision disturbances and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: A subarachnoid hemorrhage is bleeding in the space between the brain and the tissue covering the brain, often due to a ruptured aneurysm. Symptoms may include sudden severe headache, nausea and vomiting, stiff neck, and loss of consciousness or confusion.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A brain abscess is a collection of pus that develops in response to an infection or trauma. Symptoms may include headache, fever, nausea, vomiting, neurological deficits such as weakness or speech problems, and in some cases, seizures.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease affecting the central nervous system, leading to varying levels of physical and cognitive disabilities.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense, debilitating headaches, often accompanied by sensitivity to sound (phonophobia), light, and sometimes nausea and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Viral Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, caused by viral infection. Symptoms can include headache, fever, neck stiffness, or weakness.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms can include weakness, numbness, and difficulty speaking.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that connects the inner ear to the brain. Symptoms may include hearing loss, tinnitus, and balance disorders.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barré Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare neurological disorder in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks part of its peripheral nervous system—the network of nerves located outside of the brain and spinal cord.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. Symptoms can include fatigue, skin rash, fever, and in severe cases, neurological problems.

diagnoses.name: B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A deficiency in Vitamin B12 can lead to various neurological issues, including numbness, weakness, and problems with balance.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A type of nerve damage that can occur with diabetes. Symptoms can include numbness, weakness, and pain, especially in the hands and feet.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear causing severe dizziness (vertigo), ringing in the ears (tinnitus), hearing loss, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: Migraine headaches can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, usually on one side of the head. It's often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection
diagnoses.details: Common viral infections, like the flu, can lead to symptoms such as weakness, headache, and sometimes even hearing loss due to inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.details: Meniere's disease affects the inner ear and can lead to vertigo, hearing loss, ringing in the ears, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.details: This complex disorder is characterized by extreme fatigue that cannot be explained by any underlying medical condition. The fatigue worsens with physical or mental activity but doesn't improve with rest.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: Anemia, a condition characterized by a lack of enough healthy red blood cells, can cause weakness and headaches among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: A brain tumor can manifest in many ways depending on its location and size, including weakness, headaches, and hearing loss if it affects certain parts of the brain.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.details: MS is a disease of the central nervous system that can lead to fatigue, weakness, balance and coordination problems, and cognitive dysfunction.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.details: This infectious disease is transmitted by ticks and can cause a wide range of symptoms, including fatigue, headache, and in severe cases, neurological problems including hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.details: Hypothyroidism, or underactive thyroid, can cause a variety of symptoms, including fatigue, weakness, and hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.details: While not directly causing hearing loss, hypertension can exacerbate the risk of developing conditions that lead to it, alongside causing headaches and other cardiovascular issues.
